The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Friday, July 23, 2004 				 ACC bottomline swells 84%
 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT 																								Mumbai, July 22: Associated Cement Companies (ACC) has recorded an 84 per cent rise in net profit at Rs 81.23 crore compared with Rs 44.14 crore in the corresponding previous period.																								Total income during the quarter jumped to Rs 962.47 crore from Rs 828.71 crore in the same period last year. 																								In volume terms, the company sold 3.885 million tonnes of cement for the quarter compared with 3.852 million tonnes in the first quarter of 2003-04. 																								The cement industry as a whole has posted a lower growth of around 2.3 per cent in the first quarter compared with 4.5 per cent in the corresponding previous period.																								With the governments continued focus on infrastructure such as roads, cement demand is expected to rise.Elder Pharma net at Rs 5.37 crore																								Elder Pharmaceuticals has posted a higher profit of Rs 5.37 crore in the first quarter compared with Rs 3.04 crore in the same period last year.																								Income from operations increased to Rs 71.31 crore for the quarter (Rs 60.95 crore), a growth of 17 per cent.																								The improved performance is a result of the companys initiatives to strengthen its product portfolio and its focus on leveraging its distribution and marketing set up.Godrej profit rises 25%																								Godrej Consumer Products net profit rose 25 per cent rise in the first quarter ended June 30 to Rs 17 crore.																								Sales revenue (net of excise) improved 16 per cent to Rs 137 crore. Godrejs brand sales rose 21 per cent to Rs 129 crore. The company said that its new product launches strengthened its presence in the toilet soaps category. 																								Streamlining distribution infrastructure and minimising inventory levels in the hair colour category also aided the strong growth.
